<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF109-526-025  </DOCNO><DOCID>09 526 025.andM;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Government Computer News  Oct 15 1990 v9 n22 p98(1)* Full Text COPYRIGHT Ziff-Davis Publishing Co. 1990.andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>USPS might lose its savings to deficit reduction payments. (UnitedStates Postal Service)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Grimm, Vanessa Jo.andM;</AUTHOR><DESCRIPT>Topic:     Office AutomationBudgetingGovernment AgencyManagement of EDPUnited States. Postal Service.andM;</DESCRIPT><TEXT>USPS Might Lose Its Savings To Deficit Reduction PaymentsandM;Although the Postal Service finally is enjoying the financial rewards of itsautomation efforts, it may not be allowed to keep its hard-won savings.andM;Despite being removed from the federal budget last year, the service facesthe possibility of being forced to pay as much $6.8 billion over anunspecified period to offset the budget deficit.andM;Postmaster General Anthony M. Frank said such payments would wipe out theservice's automation savings.andM;&quot;This would be a grave setback to our plans to operate below inflation,&quot;Frank said at press conference during last month's National Postal Forum inWashington.andP;  &quot;The contemplated 1991 payment alone would wipe out all thosesavings&quot; from greater productivity, automation and belt-tightening.andM;Rep.andP;  Frank McCloskey (D-Ind.), chairman of the House Post Office and CivilService Subcommittee on Postal Operations and Services, estimated the firstPostal Service deficit reduction payment for 1991 at $600 million.andM;He told Frank Congress estimated the additional costs to the service wouldlead to a rate increase request within three years of another six cents perletter, on top of the five-cent rate increase expected to take effect inFebruary.andM;Frank said the action would hurt postal employee morale.andP;  In the past year,the service has been making productivity gains and cutting costs beyondearlier expectations.andP;  Postal officials have attributed these improvements toincreased automation.andM;But the prospect of seeing those gains effectively wiped out by this latestOffice of Management and Budget proposal is disheartening, Frank said.andM;&quot;We go through this trade-off every year,&quot; he said.andM;Frank said the administration is trying to make the Postal Service a cash cowthat it can milk dry to reach federal deficit targets.andM;&quot;We applaud the efforts to come to grips with the federal deficit, but theseproposals run counter to the intent of our being off-budget, which was toremove the Postal Service as a target for instant relief,&quot; he said.andO;</TEXT></DOC>